Including Accessibility from the Beginning of the Software Development Cycle

02

“Shifting Left” in the Software Development Lifecycle

There's this concept of "shifting left" in the software development life cycle.

From the early stages, it is essential to include people with disabilities as part of the audience (and project team, for that matter).

We want to avoid making accessibility an afterthought.

Throughout this section we'll cover how accessibility can be addressed in every stage of the product:

  • Requirements Gathering & Planning
  • UX & Content Strategy
  • Design
  • Development
  • QA

Disability Impacts All of Us

There are so many different ways that people move through the world and interact with computers. This includes people with disabilities.

If you are trying to design and develop for a narrow segment of people and just casting people with disabilities aside, I strongly encourage you to reconsider.

Maybe you’ve heard this one before: “People with disabilities aren't our audience.” That's so wrong because there are plenty of people with disabilities who would be your audience if your site was accessible.

Test User Interfaces with People with Disabilities

Teams almost always have hiring biases and barriers that lead to nearly every member being non-disabled. This means that teams’ experience is limited when it comes to knowing how an inaccessible digital experience will affect disabled people.

The solution is to get input from the people affected early in the process. Prioritizing hiring of people with disabilities in full-time roles is an important start. Paying people with disabilities for their time and expertise to give feedback in your design and development process is another effective way to remove biases and challenge assumptions.
